This journey has taken me on a rollercoaster mentally. Crippling anxiety that had my oncologist prescribe Xanax, bouts of depression, guilt over not being present enough for my daughter, lots of tears, and a lot of work on figuring out how to stay positive and to see the light no matter the circumstances. A lot of people ask how, as an author, I deal with people not liking my book. The truth is that if people WEREN’T out there who didnt like my art, I’d be worried. Art is subjective and is meant to make you feel. And for every person who doesn’t like my work, there’s someone out there who loves it. Who *gets* it. Who it resonates with. And those are my people. That’s who I’m writing for. Them and for myself. And because the characters literally sit in my brain and scream until I tell their story. 🤣 

So to anyone thinking of writing a book but nervous about the reception. WRITE it. Because moments like these, where you get to witness someone being moved by your art… it’s incomparable. 🥹🫶🏼
